Blair study - interpreting non-linear models

Load libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(GGally)
library(olsrr)
library(modelr)
library(psych)
library(lmtest)
library(car)
library(broom)
library(boot)

Import data

sentence <- read_csv("sentence.csv")
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  id = col_integer(),
  years = col_double(),
  black = col_integer(),
  afro = col_double(),
  primlev = col_integer(),
  seclev = col_double(),
  nsecond = col_integer(),
  anysec = col_integer(),
  priorlev = col_double(),
  nprior = col_integer(),
  anyprior = col_integer(),
  attract = col_double(),
  babyface = col_double()
)

Plot severity of crime and sentence length

scatterplot <- ggpairs(sentence, columns = c("primlev", "years"), upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size = 3)), title = "Correlation Matrix between Severity of a Crime and Sentence Length in Years")
scatterplot

Format the variables

sentence <- sentence %>% mutate(lnyears = log(years), primlev0 = primlev-1, primlev02 = primlev0^2)

Plot severity of crime and log of sentence length

ggpairs(sentence, columns = c("primlev0", "lnyears"), upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size = 3)), title = "Correlation Matrix between primlev0 and lnyears")

Create plot of primlev0 and lnyears with loess smooth

ggplot(sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = lnyears)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Relationship between primlev0 and lnyears")

Create plot of primlev0 and lnyears with straight line

ggplot(sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = lnyears)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Is there a linear relationship between primlev0 and lnyears?")

Create plot of primlev0 and lnyears with quadratic function

ggplot(sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = lnyears)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ poly(x, 2), se = FALSE) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Does a quadratic equation fit the relationship between primlev0 and lnyears better?")

Interpret quadratic model

Calculate the changing slope of primlev0

slope3 <- (-0.193) + 2*0.048*3
slope6 <- (-0.193) + 2*0.048*6
slope9 <- (-0.193) + 2*0.048*9
slope3
[1] 0.095
slope6
[1] 0.383
slope9
[1] 0.671

Interpret regression slopes in terms of percent change in years

ln.y <- function(slope, x_chg) {
  new_slope <- 100 * (exp(slope*x_chg) - 1)
  return(new_slope)
}
ln.y(slope = slope3, x_chg = 1)
[1] 9.965886
ln.y(slope = slope6, x_chg = 1)
[1] 46.6678
ln.y(slope = slope9, x_chg = 1)
[1] 95.61925

Calculate the predicted length of sentence in lnyears and in years

predgrid <- tibble(primlev0 = c(3,6,9), primlev02 = primlev0*primlev0) %>% add_predictions(exp_quad) %>% mutate(pred_years = exp(pred))
predgrid

Plot the model fitted relationship

ggplot(sentence, aes(x = primlev0, y = years)) + 
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(trans = "log") +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE, formula = y ~ poly(x, 2)) +
  coord_trans(y = "exp") +
  labs(title = "The curvilinear relationship between crime severity and sentence length", y = "Sentence length in years", x = "Severity of primary crime")

Create a factor variable for race

sentence <- mutate(sentence, black.f = factor(black, levels = c(0,1), labels = c("White", "Black")))

Create Variables for MLR

sentence <- mutate(sentence, 
                   seclev2 = seclev^2,
                   priorlev2 = priorlev^2,
                   afro_m = afro - mean(afro),
                   babyface_m = babyface - mean(babyface),
                   attract_m = attract - mean(attract))
